05201nam a22007815i 9781442657335DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182009onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426573357 a10.3138/97814426573352doi  a(DE-B1597)483047  a(OCoLC)1076415717  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a82900aNew Readings in the Vercelli Book /ced. by Samantha Zacher, Andy Orchard. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (464 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Anglo-Saxon Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tThe Vercelli Prose and Anglo-Saxon Literary History -- tStudies in the Language of Copyists of the Vercelli Homilies -- tThe Portents at Christ’s Birth in Vercelli Homilies V and VI: Some Analogues from Medieval Sermons and Biblical Commentaries -- tThe Source of Vercelli VII: An Address to Women -- tVercelli Homily XV and The Apocalypse of Thomas -- tThe ‘Homiletics’ of the Vercelli Book Poems: The Case of Homiletic Fragment I -- tThe Dream of the Rood: Cross-References -- tVercelli Homilies XIX–XXI, the Ascension Day Homily in Cambridge, Corpus Christi College 162, and the Catechetical Tradition from Augustine to Wulfstan -- tThe Reburial of the Cross in the Old English Elene -- tThe Journey Motif in the Poems of the Vercelli Book -- tThe Vercelli Book and Its Texts: A Guide to Scholarship -- tIndex of Manuscripts -- tGeneral Index -- tToronto Anglo-Saxon Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe late tenth-century Vercelli Book (Vercelli, Biblioteca Capitolare CXVII) contains one of the earliest surviving collections of homilies and poetry in the English language. The manuscript's combination of poetry and homiletic prose has generated intense scholarly debate, and there is no consensus concerning the original purpose of the compiler.New Readings in the Vercelli Book addresses central questions concerning the manuscript's intended use, mode of compilation, and purpose, and offers a variety of approaches on such topics as orthography, style, genre, theme, and source-study. The contributors include some of the foremost Vercelli experts, as well as the two most recent editors of the homilies. The remarkable essays in this volume offer the first sustained literary analysis of both the poetry and prose texts of the Vercelli Book, providing important new perspectives on a dynamic and valuable historical document.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aButler, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Thomas N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcBrine, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrchard, Andy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrchard, Andy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRandle, Jonathan T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRemley, Paul G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScragg, Donald G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharma, Manish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSzarmach, Paul E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWright, Charles D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZacher, Samantha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZacher, Samantha, ee